  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Traditional use declined, but remains important in some regions",
        "body": "Traditional method use among currently married women fell from 16.5 percent in 2022 to 14.1 percent in 2025. Withdrawal accounts for most of the level and much of the decline, dropping from 13.4 to 11.8 percent. Calendar or rhythm use also fell, from 3.0 to 2.3 percent. Even after the decline, traditional methods remain a substantial part of use in several regions."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Ilocos and Eastern Visayas stand out for traditional use",
        "body": "Ilocos Region had the highest traditional method use among currently married women at 22.3 percent, followed by Eastern Visayas at 20.4 percent. CALABARZON, Central Luzon, and Bicol were also above the national level. BARMM was lowest at 5.1 percent. This regional pattern is distinct from the modern-use map, where Davao, MIMAROPA, and Caraga stand out."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Withdrawal drives the traditional method profile",
        "body": "Withdrawal was 11.8 percent nationally among currently married women, compared with 2.3 percent for calendar or rhythm. In the highest-traditional regions, withdrawal is even more central: Ilocos Region was at 20.2 percent, Eastern Visayas at 18.3 percent, and Central Luzon at 15.0 percent. Calendar or rhythm is highest in Western Visayas at 5.2 percent, but withdrawal carries most of the traditional-use pattern."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The all-women comparison sharpens the withdrawal story",
        "body": "The same traditional-use regions appear in the all-women data, but the currently married page makes the withdrawal-heavy pattern clearer. Ilocos Region is 22.3 percent for traditional use among currently married women and 11.8 percent among all women; Eastern Visayas is 20.4 versus 12.1 percent. The comparison is useful because it shows which traditional-use patterns intensify among currently married women."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Sexually active unmarried women show a rural tilt",
        "body": "Among sexually active unmarried women, traditional use was 11.7 percent in 2025. Rural sexually active unmarried women had higher traditional use than urban women, 14.4 versus 10.3 percent. That rural tilt is more visible for traditional methods than for modern methods in the sexually active unmarried group."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Traditional use is not simply a low-income pattern",
        "body": "Traditional use among currently married women was highest in the middle wealth quintile at 16.0 percent and lowest in the lowest quintile at 10.4 percent. Education also does not form a simple gradient: post-secondary women had the highest traditional use at 18.4 percent, while women with no education had the lowest at 7.6 percent. The sharper story is regional and method-specific."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Traditional method use among currently married women declined from 16.5 percent in 2022 to 14.1 percent in 2025.",
      "Ilocos Region and Eastern Visayas had the highest traditional-use levels among currently married women.",
      "Withdrawal accounts for most traditional use, especially in the regions where traditional use is highest."
    ]
  }
